[2] Cholera - Tanzania (Kilimanjaro Region)
Date: Mon 28 Mar 2016
Source: AllAfrica, Tanzania Daily News [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201603280435.html


Same District residents have been put on alert following recent outbreak of cholera as 23 persons already have contracted the disease, almost 8 years since the Kilimanjaro Region had last such a case. The infectious disease has struck Ruvu Village and the patients are currently being treated at a camp set at Ruvu Muungano Dispensary within the district.

Same District Commissioner (DC), Mwalimu Herman Kapufi confirmed the cases and called upon the public to carefully observe improved sanitation and use of clean water. Mr Kapufi advised the public to shun away from eating cold food or prepared at unclean settings. He said out of the 23 people who were getting treatment at the camp, 7 have recovered and discharged while 16 are still admitted.

The DC said that of the 16 patients, 14 are from Simanjiro District in Manyara Region while the rest are Ruvu villagers. Expounding furthermore, the DC said by late Saturday, 26 Mar 2016, 2 patients were in serious condition.

Two Ruvu Madege residents admitted to the centre, guessed that they contracted the disease after drinking unsafe water drawn from Pangani River. One said he felt dizzy while at his farm before he started vomiting. "The problem started yesterday [27 Mar 2016] while at the farm, I felt dizzy then started to vomit. I think cholera outbreak has been caused by canal water we use from Pangani River; it is not safe at all because we share it with cattle," he guesses.

[Byline: Deus Ngowi]

